            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Darren Jones is a product of San Francisco\u2019s Fillmore District, raised in a two-bedroom flat by a Muni bus driver father and a mother who worked as a nurse's aide at SF General. His upbringing was steeped in working-class pragmatism and the sounds of the city. College was never the presumed path; a steady paycheck was. Darren, who was always better with his hands than with textbooks, graduated from high school and immediately entered the workforce, landing a job as a maintenance assistant at a downtown commercial building.\n\nFor years, he was the guy who fixed leaky faucets and changed lightbulbs. His career's turning point came during the '89 Loma Prieta earthquake. With his direct supervisor unreachable, a 19-year-old Darren took charge, calmly directing tenants, checking for gas leaks, and coordinating with first responders. Management saw a natural leader, someone who understood the building not as a floorplan, but as a living, breathing system.\n\nThis event catalyzed his ascent. The company invested in his professional development, funding certifications in HVAC, electrical systems, and safety compliance. He climbed the ladder from technician to supervisor, and finally to Facilities Manager for a bustling biotech firm in Mission Bay. He thrives on the controlled chaos, ensuring the labs where brilliant minds work are secure, powered, and functioning flawlessly. He\u2019s the anchor that keeps the million-dollar science afloat.\n\nNow 51, Darren lives a quiet, structured life in the Inner Richmond. His wife, Simone, passed away from cancer six years ago, a loss that reshaped his world into a quieter, more reflective space. Their daughter, Maya, is a recent UC Berkeley graduate, and his proudest achievement. His daily routine is a constant: the 5:30 AM alarm, a strong coffee, and the N-Judah commute, where he listens to old-school jazz and watches the city wake up. He knows the city\u2019s bones, having watched it transform from a pre-tech boom town to the global hub it is today. His aspiration is no longer to climb, but to secure a stable landing for retirement and to one day take the trip to Spain he and Simone always planned. He finds deep satisfaction in his hard-won competence and the quiet respect he commands in a world of PhDs and CEOs."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the violent shudder, then the dust and the sudden, terrifying silence. He was 19, his supervisor unreachable. But instead of panic, a cold clarity washed over him. He grabbed a flashlight and a wrench, his voice steady as he herded tenants towards the stairs. In the chaotic aftermath of Loma Prieta, checking gas lines by feel, he wasn't a maintenance kid anymore. He was the one who knew the building\u2019s heart. That night, he discovered a competence that would define his entire life.\n\n2.\nHe remembers a rare sunny afternoon in Duboce Park, maybe eight years back. Simone had a travel brochure for Spain, her finger tracing the Alhambra. They weren't planning, just dreaming. The feel of her head on his shoulder, the easy silence between them\u2014it was the blueprint for their retirement. The memory isn\u2019t sad; it's a promise. That quiet moment cemented his determination, turning a shared dream into a future pilgrimage he now must make for them both.\n\n3.\nHe remembers being ten, his father letting him ride in the empty Muni bus back to the depot. The hiss of the air brakes, the worn vinyl-and-steel smell, the familiar rumble through the Fillmore streets\u2014it was the sound of his dad\u2019s hard work. It wasn\u2019t just a bus; it was a living machine that his father commanded. That feeling rooted his understanding of the city not as a place, but as a complex system of dependable parts, a lesson he carries into his own work today.\n\n4.\nHe remembers the sea of black robes at UC Berkeley last year. When they called Maya\u2019s name, his throat tightened. He saw not just his daughter, but every extra shift he\u2019d ever worked, every calloused finger. She was walking a path he could never have imagined for himself, and he had helped lay its foundation. That fleeting moment\u2014her bright smile from the stage\u2014was the ultimate, quiet validation of his entire working life. It was a feeling of profound, complete success.\n\n5.\nHe remembers a panicked 2 a.m. call a few years ago. A lead scientist, a PhD with a string of patents, was frantic\u2014a critical freezer was failing. Darren arrived, tool belt on his hip, and saw not chaos, but a faulty relay switch. He calmly bypassed the circuit, saving millions in research. The scientist\u2019s palpable relief was less important than the quiet hum of the restored machine. It affirmed his place: he was the bedrock, the one they all relied on when theories didn't matter."
